    <text>
        <body>
            <head>64. Memorandum From the Deputy Secretary of State (<persName
                    corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>) to Secretary of State <persName
                    corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d64fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Executive Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SSI_1">S/S–I</gloss> Records: Deputy
                    Secretary <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>’s Official Files,
                    Lot 85D308, Memos To/From S 1983. Secret; Sensitive. A stamped notation at the
                    top of the memorandum reads: “<persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN"
                        >GPS</persName>.”</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1983-05-06"
                        >May 6, 1983</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>I am sending on to you <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Ed Rowny</persName>’s
                memo on “Continuing Current Discussions in Geneva.” <persName
                    corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Rowny</persName> recommends that the informal <rs
                    corresp="recnSJRlK7iIeo4Xh" type="compound-subject">
                    <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>-<persName
                        corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> channel</rs> be shifted to
                an informal <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Rowny</persName>-<persName
                    corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> channel in Geneva and that, in any
                event, the <rs corresp="recnSJRlK7iIeo4Xh" type="compound-subject">
                    <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>-<persName
                        corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> channel</rs> on <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss> ought not to operate unless <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm"
                    >Rowny</persName> is present. <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm"
                    >Rowny</persName> also outlines the specific changes in our <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss> position that he would like to discuss with <persName
                    corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> outside the formal Geneva
                negotiations.</p>
            <p>Larry is opposed to <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Rowny</persName>’s ideas on
                procedure.</p>
            <p>I recommend that you arrange for a complete review of our <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss> position and negotiating procedures as soon as you have time. <persName
                    corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Rowny</persName>’s recommendations can be considered
                in the context of that review.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Kenneth W. Dam</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d64fn2">
                        <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName> signed the memorandum
                        “KWD” above his typed signature.</note>
                </signed>
            </closer>
            <pb facs="0262" n="233" xml:id="pg_233"/>
            <frus:attachment xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
                <note>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Attachment</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Memorandum From the Head of the Delegation to the
                            <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">Strategic Arms Reduction
                            Talks</rs> (<persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Rowny</persName>) to
                        Secretary of State <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d64fn3">Secret; Sensitive. Sent through
                            <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>. Copied to
                            <persName corresp="reccOrOPn6TsvnrGI">Burt</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="recWfOZtO0phY5iDk">Howe</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1983-05-03"
                            >May 3, 1983</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Continuing Current Discussions in Geneva</item>
                </list>
                <p>As we approach the opening of the next round of <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                    </gloss> (June 8), we need to consider how to make the transition from informal
                    discussions with <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> to
                    the talks in Geneva. At the same time, we should recognize that the report of
                    the <orgName corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up">Scowcroft Commission</orgName> presents
                    us with an opportunity to streamline the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                        >US</placeName> position in a way which furthers serious negotiation toward
                    an agreement.</p>
                <p>Once the talks resume the focus of negotiation should shift to Geneva. The
                    informal exchanges we have begun with <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq"
                        >Dobrynin</persName> should be continued through private, one-on-one
                    discussions between me and my Soviet counterpart, <persName
                        corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Viktor Karpov</persName>. We should use these
                    discussions to propose a number of changes in the <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> position in return for changes in
                    the Soviet position which would bring us closer to an agreement. If, for some
                    reason, discussions with <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq"
                        >Dobrynin</persName> need to be continued in Washington, I should be brought
                    back from Geneva to participate.</p>
                <p>I recommend that I be instructed to put a deal to <persName
                        corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> along the following lines: The
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> would indicate its
                    willingness to raise the 850 ceiling on deployed <rs corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04"
                        type="topic">ballistic missiles</rs> to a number more acceptable to the
                    Soviets. We would also agree to drop some other provisions to which the Soviets
                    have strongly objected, specifically the division of the negotiation into
                    phases, the 2500 <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H" type="topic">RV</rs>
                    </gloss> subceiling, and the 210/110 subceilings. In return, the <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> would require that the Soviets
                    accept a separate ceiling of 5000 <rs corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic"
                        >ballistic missile</rs>
                    <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RVs</gloss> and a direct ceiling of 2.5 million kg of
                        <rs corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic">ballistic missile</rs>
                    <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>. We would
                    indicate our willingness to consider equal and verifiable limits on <rs
                        corresp="recqaxqBsfTYVWHfR" type="topic">cruise missiles</rs> which would
                    allow us to accomplish current plans at lower levels than those theoretically
                    possible under the current <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                    position. We would insist that the Soviets drop efforts to aggregate launchers
                    of <rs corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic">ballistic missiles</rs> and <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">heavy bombers</rs> and to drop
                    efforts to aggregate cruise missile <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic"
                        >warheads</rs> with <rs corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic">ballistic
                        missile <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">warheads</rs>
                    </rs>.</p>
                <pb facs="0263" n="234" xml:id="pg_234"/>
                <p>We will need to inform <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName>
                    that I will be instructed to continue these informal discussions with <persName
                        corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName> in Geneva. This approach would
                    require that a set of instructions be provided me separately from the basic
                    Round IV instructions which are drafted by the interagency group.</p>
            </frus:attachment>
        </body>
    </text>
